snippet.title: A SONY Stereo Demonstration! Exploring the SONY TC126 Vintage Stereo Cassette Recorder
snippet.description:
SONY made some of the finest tape recorders ever heard. They built a solid reputation on the quality of their machines. To get such quality, they sometimes employed remarkably ingenious and creative engineering.

Such is the "case" in this very special video about the restoration of one of their finer portable cassette tape recorders, the SONY TC126 CS. This unit came as a standalone stereo cassette recorder with one speaker (!) called the SONY TC126, OR as a "kit" - the SONY TC126 CS - (Complete System?) which included a stereo microphone, two outboard speakers, patch cables and a very special stereo demonstration cassette, all housed in a high impact steel grey plastic case!

********

Sponsored by:

Sponsored by The Cross of Ramplet Mystery Suspense Novel, NOW available on AMAZON KINDLE and Barnes & Noble NOOK! Follow the adventures of the Regency English Throckmorton family as they scheme their way to treasure and fortune seeking the fabled Knight's Templar Cross of Ramplet, they great lost treasure. A rollicking fun read, now available on Amazon Kindle and Barnes & Noble NOOK!

Click either link to learn more!:

Amazon Kindle:
http://www.amazon.com/Cross-Ramplet-Mystery-Throckmorton-ebook/dp/B004QGYKMI/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&m=AG56TWVU5XWC2&s=merchant-items&qid=1310352497&sr=1-1

Barnes & Noble NOOK:

http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/the-cross-of-ramplet-the-mystery-of-throckmorton-manor-garnell-thompson/1030543291?ean=2940012310132&itm=1&usri=cross%2bof%2bramplet

********

This video explores the SONY TC126 stereo cassette tape recorder that was built around the mid 1970's. The machine is unique for a number of reasons. It was one of their consumer grade machines that used a DUAL flywheel system (a feature usually only found in their professional cassette recorders), it used engineering that almost completely re-designed the cassette drive system, and it has an auto shut off system that is amazingly complex and ingenious.

But, of course, the greatest feature of this machine is its SOUND! That's where their stereo demonstration cassette came in. Unfortunately, the restored unit in this video did not have the original demo cassette. 

So the restored SONY TC126 was used to record the demo as it existed on a reel-to-reel tape as played by the SONY TC530, another incredible machine from SONY. 

The recording quality, as you will hear, is amazing, typifying the analog warmth that was  SONY's signature sound from this by gone era.

Enjoy!

*********

Copyright Disclaimer:

This is an educational video, a critique, and report on an historic piece of vintage audio electronic equipment that is no longer manufactured or sold in stores. It is covered by the Fair Use Section of  U.S. Copyright Law:

"Copyright Disclaimer Under Section 107 of the Copyright Act 1976, allowance is made for "fair use" for purposes such as criticism, comment, news reporting, teaching, scholarship, and research. Fair use is a use permitted by copyright statute that might otherwise be infringing. Non-profit, educational or personal use tips the balance in favor of fair use."

The selection of music used in this video is from a DEMONSTRATION reel-to-reel recording that SONY provided with their machines and often simply gave to the public on request. 

As far as is known, the demo musical performance reel was made especially for, or by SONY, and does NOT carry any copyright or license restrictions, as it has no such markings AND it was included with the machine to prove its ability to play high quality stereophonic music. 

Furthermore, the song used in the recording is not even identified by name, being simply announced as a "Classical Japanese composition played by the Leon Pops Orchestra, featuring the Koto."

This performance is integral to demonstrating the historical importance of this recorder and its wonderful analog sound, something that SONY was trying to emphasize at the time to set themselves apart in the very competitive cassette recorder market.

YESTERDAY WHEN I WAS YOUNG
Original French version "Hier Ancore" by: 
Charles Aznavour (1964) 
English lyrics by: 
Herbert Kretzmer 

Yesterday when I was young 
the taste of life was sweet as rain upon my tongue
I played at life as if it were a foolish game
the way the evening breeze plays with a candle flame

The thousand dreams I dreamed
the splendid things I planned
I always build to last on weak and shifting sands
I lived by night declined the naked light of day
and only now I see the years that ran away

so many crazy songs were waiting to be sung
so many crazy times that lay in store for me

I never stopped to think what life was all about
and every conversation that I can now recall
has all to do with me and nothing else at all

Yesterday the moon was blue
and every crazy day brought something new to do
I used my magic age as if it were a wand
and never saw the waste and emptiness beyond

The games of love I played with arrogance and pride
and every flame I lit so quickly-quickly died
the friends I made all seemed somehow to drift away
and only I am left on stage to end the play

snippet.title: Ernie Kovacs NBC Morning Show 04/26/1956 1/3 featuring Edie Adams
snippet.description: [From "Kovacs Corner" on YouTube.com] - After his debut over WPTZ in Philadelphia, and a brief stint at local station WCBS-TV New York, NBC programming chief Sylvester "Pat" Weaver, the father of actress Sigourney, brought Ernie to the NBC Television Network over WRCA-TV. Later the call sign was changed to WNBC-TV, which is still the NBC's flagship station in NYC. The audience seems asleep and Ernie makes a heroic effort to keep the pace of the show moving. Remember, the rules and and writing techniques that we take for granted today were just being created, tried, and tested. So little remains of these early television programs that we by circumstance may not see the very best of Ernie's material from this period. Enjoy it as an example of a surviving work. By the way, Ernie just finished a three hour stint on the WABC Radio in New York before this show!

snippet.title: "GOING HOME" - N&W J #611 (part 1 of 3)
snippet.description:
An old tape I have highlighting the rebirth of Norfolk & Western J #611 in the early 80's. Considered among the finest examples of late-era steam, these streamlined, efficient thoroughbreds were built by N&W and pulled passenger trains for nearly a decade. Fortunately #611 was saved from the cutting torch and pulled excursions from 1982-1994. This film documents the work leading up to that era. It has since been displayed at the Virginia Museum of Transportation in Roanoke, alongside another N&W excursion star, Class A 2-6-6-4 #1218. This film really captures the spirit of running one of man's most beloved creations. Both railroaders and railfans alike wait patiently for her return....

Sorry about the 3 parts- - this was uploaded before YouTube allowed longer videos.

Thanks to switchstand for the content and CoasterTroy80 for video transfer & sound.

snippet.title: BOD - Sony TC 104 Vintage Hi Fi Tape Recorder Exploration
snippet.description:
In this video, BOD stands for "Birth Of Dreams", the music that accompanies the story. In 1967 SONY released the TC 104 Hi Fi mono "tapecorder", a machine of remarkable sonic ability. I dreamed of owning such a machine, but never had the money. 42 years later, thanks to E-Bay, my dream came true. And here it is -- in all it's original glory.

This video is sponsored by:

Forestdale Tone Poems Inspired By Nature Neoclassical Music CD.  12 wide pan stereo tracks of beautiful mood enhancing and inspiring neoclassical music composed and performed by Tim Thompson with his fabulous XV synthesizer orchestra. For more information and to buy the album direct from ClydeSight Productions, or individual tracks as MP3 downloads from CD Baby, or select MP3 stores, please visit: 

http://www.clydesight.com/forestdale

*********

In the late 1960's SONY was rocking the tape recorder market with machines of remarkable engineering and quality. The SONY TC 104 monophonic hi fidelity reel to reel tape recorder was a prime example of SONY quality, simplicity, elegance and stunning sonic impact. 

The vintage tape recorder is long since gone in the market, but occasionally appears on E-Bay. I found this recorder at a very good price because it had some serious problems. It needed new belts (replaced) and the main drive idler wheel is dried and cracked with oxidation due to age. Nevertheless, I was able to coax it back into functionality and the SONY TC 104 reel to reel tape recorder has come back to life, vibrant as ever.

This video presents an exploration of the complete vintage reel to reel tape recorder including the inner mechanism with a twist.

 Instead of having me banter on and on about it, I have set the video to music, appropriately enough called: The Birth of Dreams. The musical track was recorded on this tape recorder from the wide pan stereo CD,  and is presented as a direct feed into the video camera for faithful reproduction of the tape recorder's remarkably good recording quality. Imagine a 42 year old piece of vintage equipment able to manage a modern all digital CD sound! That's SONY, they were way ahead of their time! 

Enjoy the video, and don't forget to buy the CD for even more beautiful sounds!

snippet.title: Getting  a 2" Quad Videotape to Play
snippet.description: We forget sometimes how far video technology has come in just the past few years.  I recently needed to get some video from an old 2" Quad videotape and discovered that the machines that can play them are almost non-existent, not to mention people who know how to operate and maintain them.  Also the tape manufacturers built in a time-bomb that is literally destroying these old tapes as they sit on shelves - even in properly climate controlled rooms!  My friend Larry Odham just happens to have a working Ampex VR-1200B - and he shows us what it takes.
